  "description": "Compactness is a topological property that captures the idea of a space being \u0026ldquo;finite-like\u0026rdquo; even when it contains infinitely many points. A compact space is one where you cannot escape to infinity — no matter how you try to cover it with open sets, finitely many of them always suffice. This seemingly simple condition has remarkably powerful consequences, making compactness one of the most important concepts in all of topology and analysis.\n",
  "name": "Compactness",
